	abstract = {High-pressure grinding rolls crushers (HPGR) are typically operated at constant pressure with variable rolls speed maintaining choke-fed conditions. Since this simple approach works well in practice, there has been little incentive to further study their control, and the literature on this topic is scarce. Economic model predictive control (EMPC) of mineral processing circuits faces a similar situation, because its benefits are yet to be quantified. This paper presents case studies of different process control strategies on a simulated mineral processing plant comprising an HPGR crusher, ball mill, and flotation circuit. The simulator is based on population balance modelling and is an extension of previous work. Operating costs and grinding product characteristics are linked to flotation performances to allow estimating the profits. They are used as a metric to compare advanced regulatory control to plant-wide EMPC in scenarios where identical sequences of disturbances are simulated on the feed ore particle size and hardness. The results show that in normal operating conditions, the EMPC performance is equivalent to a standard advanced regulatory scheme, but it surpasses it when plant feed rate is limited.},
